a. Harper shows that governments from the federal to the local became helplessly captivated by the idea that weather control could promote agriculture, health, industrial output, and economic growth at home, or even be used as a military weapon and diplomatic tool abroad. Clear fog for landing aircraft? There's a project for that. Gentle rain for strawberries? Let's do it! Enhanced snowpacks for hydroelectric utilities? Check. The heyday of these weather control programs came during the Cold War, as the atmosphere came to be seen as something to be defended, weaponized, and manipulated. Yet Harper demonstrates that today there are clear implications for our attempts to solve the problems of climate change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aScience and statezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWeather control - United States - History. 0aWeather controlzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aCold War.  acontrol of nature.  astate funding.  athe state.  awater.  aweather control.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022643723140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226437378zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226437378/original  a978-3-11-071193-6 University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA